column27: AnimalMemo_1
Rabbits born overnight 3/29-3/30 2025 to Mother A58071379 "Cherry Blossom"
Has a "A" in left ear

Email from FP P38703885 8/14 "Just for future knowledge whoever does take them I had to move them into an actual big puppy pen for space because they are becoming a little fighty towards each other in a smaller area and destructive. They have to be watched often and consume litter boxes, any toys, towels, rugs and any blankets are suggested to be kept away from them not even advise to let them hop on rugs to free roam as they instantly dig and start ripping it up. We only have their rabbit wood toys and all metal bowls and litter pans now for them on a concrete floor in the basement as they ate through the wooden rabbit hut i bought.  They do love to be outside but the heat makes that challenging but it seems to help relieve some evergy and create fun for them." "I have triplet daughters so I kind of get the feeling that just the three of them together are maybe antagonizing one another to be destructive.  I've had two females together in the past in one kind of created chaos so the other just followed the behaviors they were doing but as soon as I separated them out they were better off and I saw their true natures of each of them however I don't have the ability to separate out the three of them.  I have noticed out of the three there is one with a little bit more of a tude issue and then we do have one of them that just prefers to sit on the couch and watch movies with the everyone at night."
On meds through 10/15
When looking for future foster, either separate or make sure they have large enough space as they have begun fighting See memo from 8/14

6/21/2025- Rabbits A58757640 and 58757630 were surrendered this afternoon OTC as owner stated they were too much to care for and he did not realize that when he bought them from the auction last month for $5.00. I explained to surrenderer that I did not know if we had open kennels for them and that we schedule by appointment. Surrenderer stated his family told him they wanted them gone and asked where he could take them today to drop off because he doesn't want to just leave them outside somewhere. Rabbits were in a tote in the back of the surrenders vehicle and one did appear thin. Out of concern for the rabbits safety and checking if we had an open place for both rabbits, I booked both rabbits in. Surrenderer stated he had no money today after I told him what the surrender fees where and stated again that he had only paid $5.00 for them. I did send surrenderer with donation envelope. Surrenderer stated neither rabbits were given names and both have been housed together and he believes one is a female and the other is a male, no surr profile was filled out. TMC
On meds through 10/13/25.
VERY SWEET CATS ON INTAKE, NO ISSUE HANDLING, ETC.

Hello! I’m Solo! Can you help change that? I am looking for a patient and kind soul to take me to my forever home. At first meetings, I can be a little shy. New situations and people can be scary! One thing that always helps me feel better is the company of another sweet kitty like me. I love to spend time with my feline friends, cuddling, chatting and having snoozes together. With my favorite humans, I love getting gentle pets and love. With my sweet soul, gentle eyes and calming demeanor, I am sure to bring joy into any home. So don’t wait! Come on by and let’s meet!

Solo has made great improvement with enrichment. She was on top of the cat tree facing the wall upon entering the condo. Upon approaching, she stood up, came forward and solicited pets. She accepted treats and offered and returned slow blinks. She has been more active in the condo room and making use of the cat tree. This is a great improvement to her previous demeanor, hiding in the corner, retreating, hard stares, some hissing. Will remove behavior consult with continued, consistent improvement - GE 9/23/25

Shy, nervous cat but non-reactive. Will need time and patience to come out of her shell and adjust to change in new home - GE 9/9/25 Solo is continuing to do well, accepting treats and soliciting pets. Struggled with getting packed up for Trocaire but is showing continuous, consistent improvement. Will remove behavior consult - GE 9/30/25 Solo is adjusting well to his new condo-mates. Responded neutrally in the presence of Ginevra and Florenzo, came down to share treats & sniff new blankets. Will continue to monitor behavior and ensure a smooth transition - GE 10/1/25

Hey there! I’m Leia. I am a sweet, lovely girl who is looking for someone with a gentle heart and patient soul to become my new best friend! At first meetings, I can be a little shy. New situations and people can be intimidating! Once I get to know you, I will love some gentle pets and loving company. In my free time, you can usually find me curled up in the sunny rays from a big, wide window, snoozing the day away. I enjoy the calm way of life and love to relax. If all this sounds good to you, we might be a match! Come on by and let’s meet!

Leia is doing well with enrichment. She was laying on the kurunda on the shelf in the condo upon entering the room. Her body language was calm, she sat up upon approach. She did not accept treats but she did come forward to sniff my hand. She returned slow blinks. Leia has been more active in the condo room, watching people through the window. Will continue regular enrichment to work on engagement - GE 9/23/25

Hello! I’m Florenzo! When you first meet me, you’ll notice that I can be a little shy. New situations and people can be scary! One thing that always makes me feel better is the company of some kitty friends. Maybe you can relate! I love to chill with other kitties and you can usually find me and my kitty friends snuggling, playing, or having chats. If you have a cat at home or are looking to adopt more than one, then I might be the kitty for you! So, what are you waiting for? Come on by and let’s meet!

Florenzo has been doing well with enrichment. He was behind the cat tree, against the wall facing the corner upon entering the room. Upon approach, he lifted his head and came forward to sniff my hand. He accepted treats and pets. His body language remained calm. Will continue regular enrichment to work on confidence and engagement - GE 9/23/25

Florenzo is nervous and fearful in the condo room after arriving yesterday. Will spend more time in the condo, provide enrichment, and allow time to decompress before making available - GE 9/19/25 Florenzo is doing better today, out from under the cat tree, calm body language, came forward to sniff hand and accepted pets, was non-reactive but did avoid eye contact and did not return slow blinks - GE 9/20/25 Florenzo is doing better with enrichment, still hiding under the cat tree but turned to face me upon approaching, good eye contact, sniffed hand, accepted pets and returned slow blinks. Still needs work to build confidence and increase engagement with his surroundings - GE 9/26/25

Hello! We’re Abalon and Aster! The two beautiful besties who are ready for their forever home! We are best friends are looking for a home together, and to make it extra special, our adoption fee is the price of one — you get two wonderful cats for a single fee.” Of the two of us, Abalon is the more outgoing. She is incredibly social and friendly, giving headbutts to every new friend she meets! Aster can be a bit more nervous in new situations, but having her best friend at her side always helps! We are both very playful and love to play with each other or with fun toys! We also can be found snuggling, cuddling, or having chats in front of a big, sunny window in our free time. If you’ve been waiting for two kitties with golden hearts and personalities that complement each other, that’s us! Come on by and let’s meet and remember one adoption fee for both of us ! Double the love, double the fun, for the price of one!

Shyer/nervous but non-reactive. will need time and patience to adjust to change in new home - GE 9/24/25 Aster is still adjusting to her condo room, remaining on top of a kurunda bed with her head tucked/ears flattened upon entering. She did appear to relax slightly after seeing Amethyst, and did accept treats from me, relaxing her body language even more. She is a shyer/nervous girl and would do well with patient, consistent enrichment - GE 10/2/25

Heya! We’re Toaster and Poptart , a bonded pair of kitties that are *available for ONE adoption price . On first meetings, we can sometimes be a little shy, but don’t let that fool you! It only takes a bit of time until we warm up into the loveliest of lovebugs! A kind soul and sweet voice will have us rolling around in no time and our purrs are sure to make you smile! With Toaster’s sweet, round face and Poptart’s kind, big eyes, we inspire the same warmth as our namesakes! Most of the time, you can find us snuggling together in a cozy corner or in the sunlight from a big window. We love to enjoy the chill way of life, sharing low-key times with our humans. If this sounds good to you, we might be a match! Come on by and let’s meet!

Hello there, I’m Blue — a lovely lady with soft blue and white fur and a calm, gentle spirit to match. I’m friendly and enjoy being around people, but I like things to move at my own pace. I’ll happily come over for attention and affection when I’m in the mood, but I’m not the kind of cat who enjoys being picked up or handled too much. I’m looking for a quiet, peaceful home where I can relax, feel safe, and be appreciated for who I am. A calm environment — maybe with a cozy window seat and someone who understands a cat’s need for personal space — would make me the happiest girl around.If you’re looking for a sweet, low-key companion who brings warmth and beauty to your days, I think we’d make a wonderful match.

Mum was asleep in the milkcrate upon entering the room. Upon approaching her kennel, she got up, started vocalizing & flanking the kennel bars. Upon opening the kennel door, she rolled over with her head towards me, chin up, soliciting pets, purring, & kneading the air. She initiated & returned slow blinks when making eye contact. She continued to solicit pets with her chin facing up and head out of the kennel door in my lap, I was able to pet both sides of her face, forehead, chin, and down her back while she continued purring, soliciting pets, and kneading the air. Once she stood up, I picked her up and held her for several seconds. Her body remained relaxed, muscles loose, and she did not attempt to flee. After placing her back down, she once again solicited pets, and initiated and returned slow blinks. At no point did she hiss/swat or retreat/retract/advance. Her pupils remained appropriate for the ambient lighting throughout the encounter as well as ears up & forward. Based on my assessment, Mum would be an adoption candidate. - GE 10/13/25

column27: 10/10/25 ND Spoke with Frances regarding "Rico" regarding his behavior before the death of her husband. She stated that he was never really exposed to people except when they had close family or friends when they came over. He will bark and possibly lunge and some people he does not know. He has had positive interactions with kids as young as 8. He has had positive interactions with other dogs but may have a high prey drive. She stated that he can be shy and fearful until he gets to know someone. She stated that he was very high energy and active but mild mannered when he is tired. She also stated that he did well at a free vaccine clinic in line with other dogs, cats and people. She stated he was interested in what was going on but active very appropriately. I explained that we are going to be able to evaluate Rico for adoption but there is always a possibility that he may not do well in this setting. She stated that she understood. She stated that she might be here a little late as she is coming from work!

column27: Memo from Previous Owners profile: 09.23.25 ALD and DV spoke to Frances, Stating that we do not believe the shelter is the best placement for Rico due to his anxious nature and the trauma he experienced from losing his person. (Os deceased husband) O has reached out to certain fosters already, DV will send her a more comprehensive list. Rico is 2yo and they have had him since he was a puppy. Both O and her late husband are disabled and she is no longer able to fulfill Ricos needs after her husbands passing. O reported that Rico bit her brother, the same day of her husbands passing, after the paramedics left, her brother entered the house, dog approached him, and when the brother extended his hand, Rico nipped at him. O stated that there was no visible mark left on skin. O stated the Rico runs up to neighbors to play, off leash. Neighbors have come over to help. Rico jumps in greeting. O stated that she is uncomfortable let Rico off leash at the park bc she doesnt trust his recall, O states that he is very strong and due to her disability she is unable to take him on fulfilling walks. Behavior probs before Death of husband- can be hard to redirect.

column27: 10/15/25 ND Spent some time with Rico ~10 minutes. Sat next to his kennel and offered treats. He did not take. He was barking the entire time, he did perk his ears up when he heard outside or walk. He did stop barking and sniff me but was easily distracted by other dogs barking and would run to the back to investigate/alarm bark. He again approached me and sniffed me under the kennel door. ended the session here. 10/16/25 MN went to spend some time with Rico, was there no longer than 5 minutes. He was barking in the back of kennel i was at the front with treats and enrichment, he stopped barking once he saw me and walked up to the kennel, neutral face, tail wagging, easy body language, I offered treats, a bone, a food bowl and some cheese under the kennel door, reached into treat pouch for another option and he began barking/growling, lunging at the glass and tagging it where i was knelt down outside of it, stopped offering treats and walked away

column27: 9/5/2025: Per owner dog is severely allergic to chicken and will vomit and it gives her diarrhea. She likes to eat Purina One Lamb and Rice. Dog does not eat canned food. Hi, I’m Kash! I’m a big, handsome guy with a happy, wiggly personality. I love being social with people and other dogs, though I’ll admit I can be a little aloof sometimes—it’s just my way of keeping things cool and calm. Most of the time, I’ve got an easygoing vibe. I enjoy hanging out, exploring new places, and taking in all the sights and smells. I’m also pretty curious, so adventures with me are never boring! I do like snacks and treats (who doesn’t?), and I’ll happily work for them, but food isn’t the only thing that makes me happy—I really just enjoy good company. If you’re looking for a friendly, steady dog who’s equal parts fun and chill, I think we’d be a great match. I can’t wait to meet my person and start our new life together! column27: Hi, I’m Dior! I’m a sweet little lowrider with the biggest, happiest smile you’ll ever see. I’ve got a silly, goofy personality that makes it hard not to fall in love with me. I’m all about attention, cuddles, and pets—I’ll happily soak up all the love you’ve got to give! I like to greet everyone I meet with tail wags and smiles, and if you let me, I’ll climb right into your lap for snuggles. I’m also very food-motivated (treats are the way to my heart!), and I’d be thrilled to be your partner in playtime, walk time, and cuddle time. The only thing I ask is that my new home doesn’t have cats—I prefer to be the star of the show .If you’re looking for a happy, affectionate, goofy little sidekick, I think we’d be a perfect match!

column27: 9/15/25 MN can be shy at first, warms up easily, sweet and gentle, calm deminer, some pulling on leash recc harness and collar combo, calm in kennel 9/18/25 MN easily leashed in kennel, sweet and social, soliciting attention, treat motivated, interested in toys, recc harness pulls on walks, confident in new environments 9/24/25 ND Was easily leashed and harnessed in the kennel was very calm. (KS was with me) did very well outside walked well. brought into play yard she zoomed around but mainly wanted pets and treats. she got mouthy when we were walking down the hill. she was easily redirected with treats and asking for commands. walked well the rest of the walk no issues getting her back in the kennel. 9/29/25 ND Did well with harnessing. walked well got mouthy once but was easily redirected. worked on sit being an auto behavior instead of being jumpy. did very well overall today. 9/30/25 MN Did well harnessing, beginning of walk went well, easily redirected and minimal distractions, nearing end of walk had a harder time redirecting and staying focused, did leash climb and become mouthy but was put in a sit and redirected with treats, finished walk with no issues, went into kennel easily 10/1/25 ND Took Mochi for a walk with KS. She did very well harnessing. sat and waited by door way. she did well only started jumping and mouthing once but was easily redirected with a sit or asking her to go find treats. she did well coming back in the kennel no issues. 10/2/25 MN did well harnessing and coming out of kennel, easily excitable, did well redirecting for treats, was jumpy and mouthy at times but sitting/redirecting well, did well in office with enrichment and decompression time 10/3/25 MN doing well on walks, is easier to redirect when overstimulated using treats and a sit command 10/4/25 MN did well today on walk and for harnessing, very vocal when people are walking past kennels, have been working on this with Click for Calm, is easily excitable 10/6/25 MN experienced level 3 dog walking volunteer Laurie and Janis took out today and said she did great! was easily harnessed, no jumping and mouthing at leash or them! took treats nicely and was easily redirected if lost focus, will keep as a behavior dog only to walk but will continue to work with her and volunteers as long as positive interactions 10/7/25 ND Got Mochi out for a meet and greet and play time in the ed center. Leashed Mochi from the front of her kennel. Lured her with treats coming out of the kennel to encourage calm behaviors as there were many dogs barking. SHe was jumpy and bouncy while walking as usual. Started mouthing and jumping while we approach the kennel took her a little while to settle and refocus but was able to do so. We entered the ed center with potential adopter inside. She over all did well with the new person but was VERY mouthy with myself. She was able to redirect as usual with commands but was hard mouthing. she engaged in play with toys, we ended up cutting the session slightly short as she became too overstimulated. 10/8/25 ND No change in behavior. Was able to redirect when mouthy 10/9/25 MN very overstimulated today, mouthy and harder to redirect in beginning of walk but was better by the end, needs a good routine when walking to keep things consistent for her but not predictable 10/10/25 MN overstimulated today and hard to redirect, mouthing us and leash, walked with two leashes and this seemed to help, was easier to redirect and regain focus, brought into play yard and did amazing, played well and would sit/drop toys waiting for the next, did well going back into kennel 10/11/25 MN did well harnessing in kennel today, much calmer than usual, very calm on walk today not jumpy or mouthy at all, walked w a toy in mouth, did well sitting and waiting on walk, did well redirecting when seeing another dog, as well as when her toy dropped wed say 'get your toy' she'd go back to where it was dropped and continue walking calmly, will use this in future to walk and as a reward and distraction in future for walks to keep her calm 10/11/25 ND Took Mochi on another walk with GE. We used the toys again and she did very well. It was raining slightly and her toys were damp which we think made them a little less desirable to hold. She did jump and mouth me a few times, but was easily redirect with the toys. Over all did well 10/14/25 ND Took Mochi for a walk today. Was very easy to harness she was sitting the entire time. Carried toy until about halfway through the walk. Had one bout of mouthing, she grabbed my wrist and wouldn't let go, this was not as hard as usual. Was able to redirect with a toy. SHe lost interest in the toy after that but was walking very well. When I saw her start to jump I would give a verbal correction and she immediately sat. I got a treat and tossed it and asked her to go find it. She walked well back into the building and into her kennel. 10/15/25 ND Did great for harnessing. Did well initially walking with toy. Dropped it about halfway to the play yard and started jumping and mouthing. Did grab left harm hard and caused bruising and scratching through sweatshirt and fleece jacket. Was hard to redirect. Did grab right arm as well but lightly bruised. took to play yard. did well in yard and walking back in. 10/16/25 MN fine in kennel harnessing/leashing, did well as sitting at most doors before going outside, jumpy on walk in beginging then did well redirecting using toys and treats, doing well for sit breaks on walks to refocus, did well walking by people in hallway and outside, easily went back into kennel no issues

9/19/25 MN sat outside of kennel and offered treats, retreated to back of kennel but still interested in what i was offering (hotdogs) i had the slip leash out and he was doing fine, when i advanced forward slowly he began to bare teeth and lunged toward the slip leash, went back to soly offering treats and was non reactive will work further on this 9/19/25 ND SPENT SOME TIME WITH TROUBLE WITH HE PRESENTED WITH THE SAME BEHAVIORS AS ABOVE 9/23/25 ND Was able to get Trouble out of the kennel today. It took a few minutes of me sitting with him to get the leash over his head. He did initially try and bite the leash. once the leash was on he shook off and came right out of his kennel. He pulled slightly on leash and seemed slightly anxious outside. He did not use the bathroom outside but did go in the dog behavior office. He took a few minutes to warm up. Tolerated being touched but did not enjoy. He became very stiff and lip licked and whale eye. He did take hot dogs out of my hand and did engage in play with tennis balls and stuffy toys. Loosened up slightly when I tried to touch him during play, mouth was open and he was panting, tail was no longer tucked, did wag his tail when he saw tennis ball. Was unable to clip leash onto collar at this time as he was still very uncomfortable with touch. Was still very uncomfortable with slip leash going over his head (would shy away). tolerated me placing it on and taking it off. 9/24/25 ND Got Trouble out again today he was slightly more prosocial in his kennel. column27: Hi, my name is King Condrell—quite the royal name for a big, handsome guy like me! I’ve got soft white fur, a big happy smile, and a heart full of love and joy to give. I’m an easy-going kind of dog who enjoys the simple things in life: spending time outside, going for nice walks, getting plenty of pets and attention, and of course, toys and treats (those always make my tail wag!). I’m gentle, friendly, and love being part of whatever’s going on. Whether it’s lounging by your side, exploring the outdoors, or soaking up all the love and belly rubs you’ll give me, I’m happiest just being with you. If you’re looking for a loyal companion with a sweet nature and a big smile, I’d love to be your best friend. Do you think King Condrell could rule your heart?

column27: 10/2/25: Elizabeth Turner came in with "King" stating that she needs to return him because he bit her partner, who is the adopter, Ian Mancuso. ALD called and spoke with Ian who states that on 9/25/25, he attempted to take "King" on a harnessed walk. Ian states that King tried to pull and that King lunged at him on leash and bit him on the arms and leg (See attached photos). Ian states that he thinks King lunged at him because "King" realized that he was on leash. During the bite, Ian states that he called out for a neighbor to help him and that the neighbor "threatened to turn him in". ALD asked what this meant. Ian states that he is not allowed to have pets in his apartment and that his neighbor threated to inform that landlord, as "King" had been barking alot. ALD questioned why it took them so many days to come here to return "King". Ian states that he gave "King" to another person living in his apartment complex and that she took him from 9/25/25 to 10/1/25. Ian states that the person he gave the dog too couldn't keep "King" because he "barks too much". ALD and TMC got a verbal sign over from Ian. As ALD was completing contract, Elizabeth, Ians partner, states that King "tried to bite her four times" the night prior. When ALD questioned what triggered this behavior, Elizabeth states that she was trying to get him to follow commands (sit) and that he "wouldn't listen". Elizabeth states that "King" does not like long walks and that he jumps alot, leaving bruises on her upper thighs. At the end of the conversation, Elizabeth states that "King" gave Ian a panic attack the night before and that she "had to hide the knives in the home from him". Elizabeth states that Crisis Services advised Ian that he should return "King" to our care // ALD

column27: 10/15/25 - King Condrell has recently been placed on a second bite hold following another incident that occurred during a walk, nearly two weeks after his return. In this latest event yesterday, King bit a volunteer on the arm, resulting in a level two bite. We also revisited the previous bite report from King’s former owner, which involved a level three bite, also occurring during a walk. While we have not been able to determine a specific trigger for these behaviors, the pattern of incidents during walks, combined with the severity of the previous bites, raises significant safety concerns. After careful consideration, we have made the difficult decision that King Condrell is no longer a safe candidate for adoption. For this reason we are electing humane euthanasia for behavioral reasons. This can be done at the techs earliest convenience. LJA

Hi, I’m Anya! I’m a stunning girl with the most beautiful blue eyes — everyone says it looks like I’m wearing eyeliner or eyeshadow, but I promise it’s all natural! I can be a little shy when I first meet new people, but once I feel comfortable, I really open up. I love getting pets, soaking up attention, and playing with toys. I think I’d be happiest in a home with another friendly dog who can show me the ropes and help me build confidence. I’m still working on my training, so I’ll need a family who can be patient and help me keep learning. With some love, structure, and playtime, I know I’ll be an amazing companion. If you’re looking for a sweet, beautiful girl with a gentle heart and a playful spirit — that’s me, Anya!

Hi, I’m Albi! I’m a happy, wiggly shepherd boy who’s always ready to make new friends—especially if you have treats! I love attention, playtime, and getting out for walks, but I’m just as content hanging out with my favorite humans once I’ve had my fun. I’d do best as your one and only dog, so I can soak up all the love and snacks for myself. I promise to return it all tenfold with loyalty, tail wags, and goofy smiles. If you’re looking for a fun, loving companion who will always be thrilled to see you, I think we’d make the perfect match!

Hi, I’m Valentino! I’m a tall, handsome gentleman with a big heart to match my big paws. At first, I can be a little shy — new places and people make me nervous, so I’ll need a patient person who can give me time to settle in and feel safe. But once I do, you’ll see my true personality shine through! When I’m comfortable, I love going for walks, soaking up attention, and doing my happy zooms around the yard (I may be big, but I can move!). I’m a smart boy who knows “sit” and “paw,” and I’ll gladly show off my skills for a treat or two. If you’re looking for a gentle, loyal companion who just needs a little extra time and love to blossom, I might be your guy.

column27: 10/13/25 - Upon reviewing Shadow’s medical records, it was noted that the previous owner disclosed two separate biting incidents involving the same individual. The most recent occurred on August 7, 2023, when Shadow bit a neighbor who subsequently sought medical attention. The extent of the injury was not fully known, as the neighbor’s ankle was bandaged when the owner arrived to the scene. The owner also reported a prior bite involving the same person, which similarly required medical care. During the veterinary evaluation, Shadow was prescribed Trazodone to help manage anxiety and stress, and it was recommended that a muzzle be used for all future visits to ensure safety. Given the documented history of repeated aggression resulting in injury, and the associated safety concerns, we have determined that Shadow is not a suitable candidate for adoption. Therefore, we are proceeding with humane euthanasia due to behavioral reasons. This will be carried out as soon as the veterinary team is available. //LJA

column27: 10/13/25: ALD received VM from Ricardo10/6/25 stating that he is homeless and needs help caring for his dog. ALD called Ricardo 10/8/25 and spoke with him. Ricardo states that a person he knows took in his dog for rehoming. on 10/9/25, Gabrielle Rosier (716-970-3355) called and LMOM for ALD requesting a callback re a dog that she recently took into her possession. ALD called and spoke with Gabrielle, who states that she met Ricardo at a local outdoor market where she works. Gabrielle states that Ricardo informed her that he needs a home for "Storm E Girl" as he is unhoused and Gabrielle agreed to take her because she was very easy going at the market, got along with her dogs, and her nephew, Dominic Michels (716-330-9364) has been thinking about adopting. Gabrielle states that she took Storm E Girl home and set her up in the basement to adjust. Gabrielle states that Storm E Girl is very sweet and easy going with her but seems fearful of men. Gabrielle states that when her 22 year old nephew, Dominic, came over to meet Storm E Girl, she bared her teeth at him and air snapped. Gabrielle states that Storm E Girl did not break skin, but that the incident scared her nephew. Additionally, Storm E Girl growled at Dominic when he attempted to let her outside. Gabrielle expressed to ALD at the end of the phone call that she would like to continue housing Storm E Girl until she could find alternative placement for her with plans to continue socializing. ALD got VM from Ricardo 10/10/25 requesting a call back. When ALD called Ricardo 10/13/25, he states that he had to bring Storm E Girl back into his care 10/12/25, reiterating the information provided by Garbielle previously. Ricardo states that he is currently residing in his cousin's home and that Storm E Girl is unable to come inside due to other animals in the home. Ricardo states that Storm E Girl is sleeping in his vehicle and that he has been spending time with her outside. ALD called Gabrielle to discuss what changed since she last spoke with ALD. Gabrielle states that she has her five-year-old son half the time and that her child's father was not comfortable with their child staying in the same home as a dog with an unknown behavior history that has demonstrated signs of fear aggression. Gabrielle provided ALD with Dominics contact information. ALD called and LMOM after 2 rings. ALD booked surrender appt for Ricardo and emailed surrender profile to mpacellasr@gmail.com for completion prior to intake // ALD ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ 10/14/25: Gabrielle called ALD to make sure that Storm E Girl made it to the shelter ok. ALD advised that she is with us and informed Gabrielle that she was not able to make contact with Dominic. ALD emailed the bite assessment form to Gabrielle at rosiergabrielle@gmail.com // ALD

column27: 10/10/25 ND SPENT SOME TIME WITH ONYX AT HER KENNEL. UPON APPROACH SHE WAS ALARM BARKING BUT HER TAIL WAS NEUTRAL, WAGGING SLOW AND WIDE. HER EARS WERE BACK. I SAT BY HER DOOR AND GAVE HER TREATS. SHE CAME AND APPROACHED ME SHE SNIFFED UNDER THE DOOR. SHE DID EAT THE TREATS INFRONT OF ME. IF I MOVED TO QUCIKLY SHE WOULD START ALARM BARKING AGAIN. AFTER A FEW MINUTES SHE STOPPED ALARM BARKING AS I WAS MOVING TO GET MORE TREATS. WHEN I STOOD UP TO WALK AWAY SHE STARTED ALARM BARKING AGAIN. I ASKED HER TO SIT IN WHICH SHE DID AND I REWARDED AND WALKED AWAY. 10/11/25 MW Went to kennel to grab Onyx for intake services. Upon approach, she gave me very wiggly body language and jumped right up onto the kennel door. When I opened the door, she alarm barked multiple times but did not move. After sniffing my arm, she allowed me to leash her very easily. Onyx walked well into the infirmary but did have very nervous, jumpy energy. She was ok with her head and shoulders being pet, but if I stroked down to her flank, she would turn very quickly towards my hand and get stiff. During intake, she rolled over onto her back and exposed her stomach. Paige went to check for a spay scar as previous owners stated that Onyx was spayed. When Paige made contact with her abdomen, Onyx very abruptly jumped up and gave a correction/warning bite (light pressure, no marks left). At this point, we opted to muzzle Onyx for the rest of her intake services. She attempted to remove the muzzle several times, but we were able to perform all intake services. Even with the muzzle on, Onyx seemed very reactive whenever Paige had to touch her flank. Once intake services were finished, Paige and I tried once again to verify a spay scar but Onyx was too stressed out. She did allow me to walk her back to the kennel, remove the leash, and apply Revolution without any issue. 10/11/25 ND Spoke with MW about incident noted above. Went to visit Onyx later in the afternoon. She initially was alarm barking but as I started speaking to her she became wiggly. I tossed her treats and would reward her for looking at me and not barking. Kept session short as she had a stressful da 10/15/25 ND Spent some time with Onyx outside of her kennel. She did well without alarm barking and approached in a cautious but prosocial way. Did get spooked and ran to the back of her kennel. Seemed very timid after will attempt to remove from kennel on 10/16

?? Meet Madam Sophia the Hen & Papi the Rooster – A Feathered Friendship in Need of a Home ?? Madam Sophia is a darling little Rhode Island Red-type hen with a gentle heart and a touch of shyness. She hasn’t laid any eggs yet, but she’s full of potential and even more full of love. Ruby is friendly, curious, and sometimes a bit chatty—especially when she’s feeling brave! By her side is her loyal protector and best friend, Papi, a stunning and kind-hearted rooster who looks out for Soph with all the grace and charm a rooster can muster. Papi is not only beautiful to look at, but also incredibly sweet and easy to be around. These two share a strong bond, and our wish is for them to be adopted together, so Sophia can continue to feel safe and loved with Papi watching over her. If you’re looking to add a little love, fluff, and friendship to your life, Ruby and Papi would make the perfect addition to a caring flock or family. ?? Message us for more info or to meet this adorable duo!

?? Meet the Dashing Dappled Rooster, Papi ?? Looking for a stunning addition to your flock? This beautifully dappled gentleman is as eye-catching as they come! With feathered legs, striking Americana and Easter Egger-style markings, and a proud, full-grown frame (though still young at heart!), he's a true head-turner. Whether he's strutting through the yard or keeping a watchful eye on his flock, this rooster brings both beauty and presence to any coop. He comes with a special request — to be adopted alongside his companion, a small, sweet Rhode Island Red pullet. She's young and full of personality, and they make a charming pair. They've bonded well, and we’d love for them to stay together as they find their forever home. While we don't have a birthdate on file, both birds are healthy, vibrant, and ready to settle in with a caring family. ?? Ready to give this feathered duo a happy home? Reach out today and let these two strut their stuff into your heart!

Hi there, I’m Luka — a sleek, handsome gentleman with a few silver hairs of wisdom sprinkled in. I might be a senior, but I’ve still got plenty of charm, curiosity, and love to give. When you first meet me, I might take a little time to settle in and get comfortable with my new surroundings — I like to make sure everything feels just right before I show my true, affectionate side. Once I do, though, I’m all about being social and soaking up your attention. I love gentle pets and company, but sometimes I can get a bit overstimulated — it’s just my way of saying I need a little personal space for a moment. With someone patient and understanding, I’ll make a loyal, loving companion who enjoys your presence and brings a quiet confidence to your home. If you’re looking for a friendly, handsome boy who appreciates both affection and independence, I think we could be a perfect match.

Tiffany P0047944596 called and left a message with concerns about her foster kitten's, Bingo, behavior. She has two kittens fostering for socialization. I called and she said Bingo hisses when she tries to pet her and "freaked out" when she was holding her to introduce her to a friend. I explained the importance of positive reinforcement, going at the animal's pace, and not forcing them into scary or uncomfortable situations. It seems like she and Bingo have a good relationship, but she's worried about her doing well with new people. I told her to, for now, start at square one for new people, don't force interactions, and use positive reinforcement to build positive associations with new people. - GE 9/24/25

column27: 9/24/25 MN still shy and retreating into back of kennel, sat outside offering treats and after about 30 seconds came to the front still shy and retreating at fast movements, loud noises, or people passing by and were retreating again into the back but recovered quickly 9/29/25 ND Did a meet and greet with Flip for foster care. Potential foster had 2 other dogs one small and one larger. They also had a four year old daughter. Flip was very reactive towards the other dogs. we were trying to make positive associations. Potential foster parent was a very loud and pushy man which did not seem to work in Flips favor. we did not think it was the right fit for Flip especially because of the reactivity. The potential foster parent did not seem to be open to management strategies. As he was planning to "just throw the dogs together". 10/3/25 MN did a meet and greet today for a behavior foster placement and he did well, immediate upon coming into room was tail wagging, neutral body language. he was nervous of the other dog but taking treats well and soliciting attention, made a few attempt to sniff other dog who shut him down( she's a nervous/anxious girl) he did well redirecting and giving her space and being social with individuals in the room, decided not best fit due to resident dog being very anxious and uninterested in flip, Went to hang in Ellies office for socialization time for afternoon foster care is reaching out to fosters of litter mates to see if another can be placed, Ellie also offered to foster for night/possibly weekend

column27: Called finder yet again to inquire about their interest in taking this kitten. Her daughter had not called as previously expected. Spoke to finder who explained that she had misunderstood my instructions. When I had said the kitten will need "one month in foster care", she misunderstood and thought that it needed one month in shelter. I clarified the instructions and the finder said she would contact her daughter with the correct information (she had refused to give me the daughter's phone number and said she would prefer to contact her herself). I stated that we would give her until end of business TODAY (9/24) to make contact and that if we did not hear from either of them, we would move forward with sending this kitten into another foster home (kitten does have someone else interested). Will update if/when we hear back. Julie T.

FP called concerned that kittens are not eating well, they are refusing to be syringe fed and when she puts slurry in a bowl for them they act interested but FP doesn't think they are actually eating the slurry. She also reported that one of the kittens is acting lethargic. She said that is needs to return the kittens as they are becoming to much for her, I told her that as it is close to the end of the day, that if she can keep them overnight we can schedule a time for tomorrow for her to bring them in to be returned and seen by a vet tech. I also told her to check the kittens throughout the night and if she notices that they are acting lethargic she can put caro syrup, maple syrup, or sugar water on their gums. Scheduled return/ tech check for tomorrow 9/24. PP

FP emailed that the 3 kittens are not eating kibble and are somewhat food focused when they are fed. She is currently feeding 1/2 can wet food per kitten BID in 3 bowls. The kittens will growl and push around the bowls. Recommended that since they are not eating kibble she use 2 cans wet food BID for the 3 kittens and put in in multiple bowls so they have increased access to food. Also recommended feeding throughout the day if possible instead of breakfast and dinner. If not possible, continue with BID feeds with increased access to bowls. CM 10/14/25

9/19/2025: Per LW: SPCA was short staffed so Jen Gorski from the CBAS transported Chapo A59393545 for us as owner was supposed to bring to us but her ride fell through. Spoke with ALD and dog was booked in medical field surrender as LW gave me an SPCA road surrender form and when I booked the dog in I booked the dog in under the owner's name and used her phone number as her signature. ALD is aware and will notify BW dog is on the way. Per ALD the owner was quoted a crazy amount from GA E Clinic and owner wants dog back. Since owner was not here at time of surrender SPCA will have to notify owner to apply for CC or put through Vet Billing if possible. SMV

9/20/25: ALD SWO- relayed medical notes to her and advised that vet staff/BW will followup early next week to discus RTO. O states that police report is filed and that insurance is involved. ALD discussed payment, advising that we typically charge between $600 and $1200 in these cases depending on severity and scope of tx. ALD advised O apply for care credit in the meantime. // ALD

Called O and told her that Chapo is ready to go home. She was worried about finances and I explained we would work with her. She said she needed to get a hold of her husband to figure out when they could pick him up. I stressed sooner rather than later because he's getting increasingly more upset with us. BW
O called back and said she will be able to pick up at 1pm today. BW

9/30/2025: Per TMC per BW, BW quoted $900 to owner. Owner was suppossed to come in 9/26 and no showed and then no showed 9/29/2025. Owner came in this morning and when I told owner it was going to be $900.00 she said she spoke with BW and BW told her she could pay $50.00 deposit and then when the court settlement came through from the person that hit the dog she would sign the check over to SPCA to pay the $850.00 balance??? I ran this by BW who said she never told her that. After back and forth SPCA will put Chapo into SPCA foster care as the dog will need several bandage changes and the owner does not qualify for Care Credit. I explained to the owner that we will put the dog in foster which means he will remain the SPCA's property until medically cleared and then BEFORE we return the dog legally to her we will process the $900.00 plus $25.00 fee through Vet Billing IF she has not received money from the settlement....BW is good with this arrangement. I also discussed this with Chief Wood as I wanted an Officer to reiterate that the dog is SPCA property until medically cleared and that the owner MUST show up for all medical follow up appointments! Per RR per Dr. Kean bandage will be changed this afternoon and owner can come in at 3:00pm to pick up dog. I did update all the owner information and will notify Foster Care that she will be here at 3:00pm. SMV
Owner NC/NS pickup appointments on both 9/30 at 3pm (shannon called to reschedule) and 10/1 at 10am *******Owner's husband showed up at 11am*********

10/1/2025: Per LMW/81: Spoke with owner of Chapo Otis and explained that the dog is the SPCA's legal property and currently a foster dog until the SPCA Vet clears him from all medical treatment and that he and his wife must show up for all follow up appointments and if they fail to do so the dog will be seized by the SPCA. Once the dog is done being medically treated by the SPCA the SPCA will process the $900 plus the $25 fee through Vet Billing and then once that is completed the dog will be RTO'd to them. SMV

Upon arrival F Anna answered the door, said the dogs were in the backyard eating. Asked to see them and she brought us back there. Two Shepherd puppies, brown and black ~4 months old tied to fence by their leashes and one F pitx free roaming the yard. F pitx AAGF, but the puppies appeared very thin. Asked Anna who the owner of the dogs is, she stated that they are watching the puppies for someone and they have had them for a couple of weeks and that they came to them thin. She said they have been feeding them rice to "bulk them up", asked if they had dog food and she said her partner just went out to buy some. She also stated that the puppies spend a good amount of time outside because they are not fully potty trained and have been "having the runs" recently. She called her boyfriend, Johnathan Negron, and put him on speaker phone and he said "I'm at work, my dogs are fine" and stated that he is the owner as they are in his care. At this point asked the Anna again who the owner of the dogs is and she shrugged and said "I guess his, I'm about to have a baby so he deals with the dogs". Asked how long they will be watching the puppies, she said at least another couple weeks. The dogs have tags on their collars with the name Brian Harrison and a phone number 607-765-8587. Since they would not provide us with any owner information, told multiple lies while speaking with us, and multiple people are supposed owners, dogs were seized and removed. Notice given to claim at the shelter. Bowl of what appeared to be rice and something else on the table between the puppies. LW/128

column27: 11/13/2023 SR 2:00Pm ~ 30 minutes I had Noble out for a walk and some enrichment. She did not have much interest in toys but she was a lot more engaged during the walk. 11/14/2023 Sr 11:00AM Noble did well on her walk. She appears to be positively interested in other dogs and I believe I will coordinate a meet and greet with fellow staff members. As this will make her more marketable for adopters. 11/15/2023 SR 12:48PM Noble was good on her walk and walked well. Nothing notable. 11/17/23 ND I took Noble for a walk this morning. offered treats in the kennel which she did take before I leash her. No issues putting the leash on. She was really great outside, she is very fun and bouncy. She was very interested in exploring the environment. No issues fitting her for a collar or bringing her back to the kennel. Really great gal!! 11/20/2023 SR I had Noble out for a walk and some enrichment. She walked well on leash and was very excitable jumping up on my every so-often to solicit attention. When brought back to the behavior office she was mildly mischievous but overall well-behaved. Obsessed with food as expected. 11/21/2023 SR ~ 30 minutes Upon approach at her kennel she was giving me soft eyes, demand barks and some wide wags. She readily went up to the kennel and jumped up when she saw me. She was very high-energy when I entered her kennel but allowed me to leash without issue. She used the restroom outside and pulled intermittently but otherwise good walker. I gave a bath and washed her twice but she still is pretty odorous. Behaved ok but still not a fan of the bath. 11/22/2023 SR ~ 15 minutes I took Noble out for a walk after sometime surgery. Nothing notable as she was a shell of her former self after surgery. Used the restroom outside without issue. 11/27/2023 SR ~ 25 MINUTES I took Noble out for some enrichment and a walk. She walked well and was well-behaved for most of the walk. Very playful when brought into the enrichment room and let go of toys when asked. Before the walk, she had a meet and greet with Miley (A0054811914). When approached at the fence she displayed some stiff body but offered appropriate sniffs. When Miley entered the same yard she was very vocal and whining while pulling to get to her. When they were able to meet face to face she was interested and mostly appropriate but very high-energy. She appeared to be too much for Miley and Miley offered some low-growls when Noble placed her head on top of hers before jumping towards her. 11/28/2023 SR ~ 30 minutes Brought Noble back in from kennel and brought her to Education center (left side) for some playtime. She was very well-behaved and we worked more with impulse control. She appears to be already well-trained but still very forward when it comes to meeting new people or going through doors. Easy fix by working on wait and until she is give a command like "go ahead" or similar when the appropriate behavior is displayed. We played fetch approximately 8 times engaged in a chase game a couple times before ending session. 11/29-30/2023 SR ~ 45 -1 hour each I took Noble for a walk and fitted her for a new harness and leash. Walked well with new harness and stayed at an appropriate distance from me when walking. She was very agile and treat-motivated during her play session. Responded appropriately the chase game and responding to commands. Better with waiting for toys but still needs more work. She is really good with jumping as high as she can for her toys. In addition, I brought her in to meet my ARK group and she was very appropriate and borderline gentle when it comes to taking toys and. She was more on the rough side when it comes to taking treats. 12/02/2023 SR I had Noble out for a walk and some enrichment time in the room. She was great as usual. No issues. 12/11/2023 SR I had Noble out for a walk and some playtime in the ed center. Great and very responsive to commands. 12/12-13/2023 SR 3:30PM She did well in her play session as usual. Appears to enjoy jumping high for her toy. Very responsive to recall and directions when prompted.

column27: Hello, hello! My name is Noble! What’s yours? I am a super-friendly pup who loves meeting new people and I love getting all the snuggles I can! In fact, I am a very determined cuddler, there’s not a lap I won’t climb into! If I don’t have a snuggly human to get my love from, I also enjoy stuffed animals and cuddly blankets. Fun fact about me, I have a habit of tilting my head at anything that piques my interest. That is sure to make movie nights fun when me and my favorite person are cuddling on the couch! If you think I might be the dog for you but you still aren’t quite sure, don’t worry! So what are you waiting for? Come on by and let’s meet!

textbox10: In If the Fur Fits - Trial
column27: Hi there, my name is Noble and I’m a big, sweet girl with an even bigger heart. At first, I might seem a little reserved, but once I get to know you, my true personality shines through—I’m a total cuddlebug! Don’t be surprised if I try to climb right into your lap (yes, I know I’m a little big for that, but I can’t help myself when it comes to snuggles). I love to play and be silly, and I’ve got a goofy side that will keep you smiling every day. I’m also a smart girl—I already know sit, stay, paw, and down, and I’d be happy to keep learning more with you. Walks are one of my favorite activities, and I enjoy exploring the world with my person by my side. One thing to know about me—I need to be the only dog in the house. I’ve got so much love and personality to give, I promise I’ll fill your heart and home all on my own. If you’re looking for a loyal, affectionate, playful companion who can make you laugh and also melt your heart with cuddles, I think we’d be a perfect match. Could I be your Noble girl? Click PLAY to watch my video !

column27: Hi there, we’re Missy and Karma — two big best friends with even bigger hearts! We’re a bonded pair of gentle giants who do everything together — naps, walks, playing in the water, and snack time (our favorite time of day!). Being with each other gives us comfort and confidence, so we’re looking for a home that can welcome both of us . We’re super smart — we already know sit, stay, and down, and we’re always up for learning more (especially if treats are involved). We love going for walks, splashing in the water, meeting new people, and soaking up all the love and attention we can get. We’re affectionate, social, and very in tune with our people. Because of our size and strength, we’re hoping to find a home with experience with large dogs — someone who understands the joys and responsibilities of having two big cuddle bugs around. If you’ve got room in your heart (and on your couch!) for two loyal, loving companions, we promise we’ll fill your life with double the love, double the loyalty, and double the tail wags.

column27: F2A parent Kennedy Sparks was a NO CALL/NO SHOW for her vet recheck appointment on Monday (10/13) at 3:00 pm. Called and spoke to her directly. She explained that she was stuck at work and didn't think that it was necessary to call and cancel. I explained that it was necessary to get the kitten in ASAP for the suture removal. She stated that she has to work most days and that coming in was basically impossible. She offered me a tentative date which was 2-3 weeks from now. I explained that we can not wait that long to do the recheck and remove the sutures and that she needed to come in this week for the exam. I offered her any day and any time with multiple options for the recheck which she all declined. She gets out of work on Thursday at 3:00 pm so I offered her a 4:00 pm slot with foster care hoping that the vet staff would be able to examine the kitten (vet appointments are not normally done on Thursdays). She accepted that day/time and said that I "left her with no choice." Julie T.

column27: Hi! We're Lilly and Mandy - a pair of pretty, petite ladies looking for a new home together! Don't let our age fool you - we're full of life, love, and a healthy appreciation for snack time. We're social butterflies who love meeting new people and exploring new places. Whether it's a walk around the block or sniffing out some fun, we're confident, curious, and always ready for a little adventure. We also adore cuddling up at the end of the day - sweet, gentle, and loyal, we're the perfect pair to bring warmth and joy to your home. Our favorite things? Treats (obviously), short strolls, cozy spots in the sun, and each other. We've been together our whole lives, and we'd love to spend our golden years with someone who appreciates our charm and companionship. If you're looking for double the love, double the cuteness, and double the fun, we're your girls. Come meet us - we can't wait to show off our tiny struts and big personalities!

column27: Hi, I’m Colt — a gentle old soul with a big heart and an easygoing spirit. At this age, I’ve got the whole “calm and cool” thing down. I’m the kind of dog who likes to find a cozy spot, lay down, and quietly take in everything happening around me. I’m a great listener, an even better companion, and I’ll always be nearby, just enjoying your company. I’m sweet and social — I like meeting new people and other friendly pets too. I’m not the wild toy-chasing type, but I do have a soft spot for a good squeaky toy every now and then. If you’re looking for a mellow best friend who will always have your back and fill your home with love and quiet joy, I might be your guy. Let’s take life slow and sweet — together. Click PLAY to watch my video !

column27: FP left message giving us an update on her kittens diarrhea, she said they are still having soft bloody stool since being on the psyllium husk powder, but she has seen some improvement. I called her to let her know I spoke with our vet and we are going to send a dewormer home for all of the kittens and we are going to decrease the psyllium from 1-2 tsp to 1/4-1/2 tsp as the were dose incorrectly and this may be the reasons for the continued soft stool. I told her that we are going to do another phone recheck with her in 10 days to assess if the soft bloody stool has resolved. If they are still having issues they we will have her bring in a fecal sample so we can send out a Idexx GI panel and we will send a fecal cup with her when she picks up the dewormer. Schedule phone recheck for Friday 10/3. PP

column27: Hey there, Puddin’! I’m Puddin Pot Pie! And yes, I sure am as sweet as my name sounds! With my calico patches and cozy little eyes, this kitty is perfect for an afternoon snooze and tea. On first meetings I can be a little slow-going, but I am as friendly as can be! I love getting pets, especially head rubs, and I love treats! I am very vocal and love to chat all about my day, and hear about yours! If you’ve been waiting for the perfect friend to curl up with and enjoy some lazy lovin’, that’s me! Come on by and let’s meet!

column27: Hi, I’m Rockford, a kitty with a soft spot for snacks and a serious talent for lounging. I’m all about that low-key lifestyle. Give me a quiet, older children / adult home, a cozy nap spot, yummy treats, and I’m one happy cat. I get along well with other feline friends, and their company helps me feel secure as I get to know my new surroundings. I may be bashful in new situations, but no worries, a calm presence and a thoughtful human will go a long way and help me settle in as I find my confidence. If you’re looking for a chill companion with a knack for peaceful living, come meet me. I might just be your purrfect snack-loving sidekick.

textbox10: In If the Fur Fits - Medical
column27: I am a playful little kitten that’s always up for fun and making people laugh! Whether I’m chasing after toys or pouncing on imaginary prey, I bring a spark of joy to every moment. I can’t wait to find my forever family and have someone to play with and snuggle up next to when I get tired. Come visit me and let’s start our fun-filled journey together! You can find me at: Pet Supplies Plus Orchard Park 3213 Southwestern Boulevard Orchard Park, NY 14127 (716) 539-9910 To be able to adopt me you will need to be pre-approved! There are multiple ways to get pre-approved: You can come to the adoptions entrance of the SPCA Serving Erie County to get an adoption pass. We are located at 300 Harlem Rd, West Seneca, NY 14224. Adoptions is open Monday - Saturday from 11am - 6pm. You can fill out our Offsite Adoption Questionnaire and email the form to offsite@yourspca.org. Link to the questionnaire: https://yourspca.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Offsite-Questionnaire-Fillable.pdf. Or you can call the Offsite Department at (716) 875-7360 ext. 235. Emails and phone calls will be returned Monday - Friday between 8am - 4pm. My adoption fee is CASH only and I cannot be put on hold for you. To verify that I am still available for adoption please contact the store. I am excited to find my forever home!

textbox10: In If the Fur Fits - Medical
column27: Hi there, I’m Mint Ting A Ling—yes, like the ice cream flavor, but way cooler and with way more personality. I’m a quiet, sensitive soul who takes life at my own pace. New places and loud noises can make me a little unsure, so I’ll need a gentle, understanding human who can offer me time, patience, and a calm space to settle in. But don’t worry—I’m not all shy and no shine. Once I feel safe, I’ll reward you with peaceful companionship and a soothing presence that only a cat like me can bring. I really enjoy the company of other mellow, friendly cats. They help me feel secure, and I learn from their confidence—kind of like feline emotional support buddies. If your home has a calm vibe, a cozy corner, and a heart open to a slow-blooming friendship, I just might be the one for you. Come meet me and let’s see if we’re a purrfect match!

column27: Hi, I’m Livia. I’m a gentle, sweet girl with the prettiest pair of blue eyes you’ve ever seen—they’ll melt your heart in an instant. I’m calm and easygoing, the kind of dog who loves a peaceful day spent near my person, just enjoying each other’s company. I do like my toys and treats (what dog doesn’t?), but mostly I just want to be close to you, feeling safe and loved. I’m past all the puppy chaos, so I’m a perfect companion for someone who appreciates a loyal, steady friend by their side. If you’re looking for a loving soul to share your days with, I think we’d be perfect together. I’m ready to give you all the love in my heart—and I have plenty to give.

column27: Hi there, I’m Zane — your future buddy! I’ve got energy for days and I’m always ready for fun. Whether it’s zooming around the yard, tossing toys in the air, or proudly carrying my favorite toy wherever I go, I’m happiest when I’m moving! I’m also a pretty smart guy — I already know sit, stay, leave it, and down. Treats are my absolute favorite, so I’m always eager to learn more if snacks are involved. After a busy day of fun I am always ready for a little cuddly chill time with my favorite people. I do need to be the only dog in the house so I can have all your love (and all the toys!) to myself. If you’re looking for a playful, enthusiastic companion who will keep life exciting (and keep you smiling), I’m your dog. Let’s go play!

will work more on him not being so jumpy in/out of kennel when leashing, finish evaluating beginning of this week. did well coming out of kennel and spent time in beh office decompressing w enrichment Dropped toy and started leash climbing while coming back into the building. Again took a few tried to get him to redirect. Redirected him and he started leash climbing was unable to get him to stop leash climbing until he was in his kennel. 9/18/25 MN doing well coming out of kennel, playing in yard or office then being harnessed, walking better less pulling but still present, walked w a treat in mouth whole walk and did great with distractions outside, came into office easily for enrichment and decompression time, redid resource testing, will redo Dog to Dog testing on 9/18 before moving him up 9/19/25 MN did well coming out of kennel and harnessing for walk, half way through walk(while walking w a toy) started leash climbing and pulling back towards building, circled back cutting walk short and went into play yard where he ran around and played with stuffed toys, went into new kennel no issues 9/20/25 MN no issues harnessing in kennel, wiggly, walks well on harness some pulling, will leash climb if a toy is not on walk w him, went for long walk then to socialize, did great in office alone (knocked some papers off desk) no inappropriate chewing, got pictures for website taken and was great, did not react once 9/22/25 Brought Zane to the Infirmary for his lepto vaccine booster. He was fine until I bent down to see how he would react to restraint with arm around the neck (I suspected he might be reactive), he did immediately jump back and air snap at me (no contact.) I gave him lots of praise and took him out in the play yard and played with him for a few minutes. He interacted with me and showed no resentment or distrust. column27: Meow….I’m Mo, a lovely little lady with a sweet personality and a soft voice that I’m not shy about using to say hello. I’m friendly and affectionate, but may be bashful at first, as I adjust to my new surroundings. I would be delighted to get a little extra help with grooming – it makes me feel pampered, cared for, and like I just stepped out of a kitty day spa! I would very much enjoy my golden years with sunny windows, the extra brushing sessions, and occasional midnight karaoke performance - you’ll love it, I promise! Stop by and meet me. If we’re a perfect match, I would love the chance to be yours!

column27: 8/25/25: Finder brought in dog that was HBC in his own neighborhood, states that he saw the driver leave the scene and a crowd of onlookers looking at the injured dog. Finder put the dog in his personal vehicle and took the dog to Buffalo Small Animal, where they stabilized and advised bringing him to SPCA if they cannot afford to hospitalize or euth. Finder states that he was not comfortable euthanizing, as he has seen the dog walked by another man in the neighborhood in the past. Finder states that he does not know any of the owner's information at this time, but that he knows he has numerous dogs, some of which are very thin. ALD informed O that dog is booked in as a stray and that the Dr. is evaluating him now. Finder wants to know if it would be possible for him to adopt the dog. ALD advised that our prognosis is guarded and that the first step would be finding the owner. ALD provided her extension and dogs animal ID to finder, as her is going to canvas the neighborhood in search of the owner. // ALD 9/2/25: ALD called finder ((716) 486-8817) to see if he was able to finder the owner. Finder will call back to discuss after rounds 9/5/25: Finder called back to discuss and LMOM for ALD 9/2/25. ALD called back and LMOM for finder to discuss.

column27: This cat was abandoned in an apartment, after an eviction for more than a month. While crews were cleaning out the apartment of the things that the tenant had left behind, there was no sighting of the cat. The crew assumed the cat had been taken by the owner or the SPCA (who the owner was in contact with) the owner assumed that the cat was taken to the SPCA by the clean out crew and their boss Joe Miranda, or picked up by the SPCA. The SPCA assumed that the owner got someone to take the cat. No one was in communication with each other. On Monday 9/8 the owner of the property arrived with Joe Miranda to find the cat in the locked apartment sitting in the window. Upon entering the apartment the cat appeared extremely skinny and thirsty. Taco meat and a bowl of water were offered to the cat who devoured both immediately. the SPCA was contacted and Joe offered to bring the cat to the shelter. Agents were dispatched to the location but then would not take the cat from Joe since he had no eviction paperwork. Joe was then directed to get the cat and bring it to the SPCA. Upon arrival at the shelter the cat was booked in under the person who left it behind and not Joe Miranda. I spoke to TMC and she was going to change it but that hasn't been done yet. Ashley D about how this should have been booked in and she is going to look at it. Ashley asked me to put this memo in. KM

column27: Hi, I’m Zeus! I’m told I’m soooo handsome — with long, luxurious fluffy fur and the most striking green eyes you’ve ever seen. I can be a little shy when I’m in new places or meeting new people, but once I feel safe, my friendly and social side shines through. I enjoy making new friends (especially if they come bearing treats… I love treats!) and I’m looking for someone who’ll give me the time and patience to settle in and show my sweet, affectionate side. If you’re looking for a stunningly handsome, gentle companion who just needs a little time to warm up, I might be your purrfect match.

column27: Hi, I’m Leo! I’m a sweet, happy, and social guy who just loves being around people. I’ve got a fun, spunky personality and a little bit of goofiness that will definitely make you laugh. I enjoy going for walks and I’m a good walker, especially when I know there might be treats involved—because treats are one of my favorite things! I’m also a big fan of pets and attention, and I’ll happily soak up all the love you’re willing to give. Whether we’re out on an adventure or just hanging out together, I’m always ready to bring joy and smiles. If you’re looking for a friendly, playful companion who will keep life full of fun, I think we’d be a perfect match! Click PLAY to watch my video !

column27: 9/29/25 ND Dog was very nervous in her kennel, she was panting and sitting in the corner, offered treats which she did not take. Once other dogs started barking she cornered her self more. 10/1/25 ND Spent some time with Irina at her kennel. she would take treats from me but was uncomfortable with me petting her/trying to get a leash on her. will attempt to get out on 10/2 10/2/25 MN Came out of kennel/easily leashed, shy/anxious in and out of kennel , walks okay on a leash some pulling or stalling, is curious and interested in people and new places but not soliciting attention, will tolerate touch, shaking and trying to hide in office, calmed down some but not fully 10/3/25 ND Took Irina outside. she did well for leashing was fearful but was able to go slow. she generally did well outside but was very nervous of loud noises. No issues walking back into the kennels 10/4/25 MN easily leashed, no issues coming out of kennel, went right outside but was nervous of the loud noises, did a very short walk outside then into office, curious new environments but cautious, not interested in treats or toys, soliciting attention very gently, licking hands, legs, sitting at feet, leaning into me, would tolerate touch to a point, seemed to prefer being up close 10/6/25 MN very loud in kennels today, easily leashed in kennel but started pulling away into back the louder it became, offered treats and un slipped leash, did not take treats but tolerated presence until it calmed down in back, did not push any further 10/7/25 ND Upon approach to her kennel, Irina was sitting on her bed. When she saw me she started to wag her tail and started to turn her belly up. I opened the door and knelt down, she approached and tolerated me clipping the leash, I went very slow as this made her slightly nervous. She followed me out of the kennel area. She was nervous walking down the hallway and was startled by the noise the door made but she was able to rebound fairly quickly. we went for a long walk and she did very well. Was slightly jumpy if there was a loud noise from the road or highway but she was able to work through it. Did engage in sniffing. Did well coming back in the building, again got spooked by the creaking noise the door made. overall did well. 10/9/25 ND Took Irina on a walk this morning. She did very well. She walked well and approached LA's dog Fiona. She was apprehensive but prosocial. No issues getting back in the kennel.

column27: Hi, I’m Irina! I’m a gorgeous red and white husky with bright blue eyes that everyone seems to fall in love with. I’m a little timid at first, but once I get to know you, you’ll see my sweet and gentle side shine through. I love people — especially when I can lean in close or sit on your feet just to be near you. I really enjoy spending time outside, feeling the breeze and exploring the world around me. I think I’d do best in a calm, peaceful home where I can relax and feel safe. Having another friendly dog around would be wonderful too — they help me feel more confident and playful. If you’re looking for a beautiful, tender-hearted companion who just wants to be close and loved, I’d be so happy to meet you. Love, Irina

Hello! My name is Gia, I love to squeak, explore, and munch on crisp veggies whenever I get the chance. Running through tunnels and showing off my zoomies are some of my favorite ways to play. All I need is a cozy home, tasty snacks, and a little attention to keep me happy. If you’re looking for a fun little buddy who brings joy with every wiggle, I would love to meet you! Stop by and let’s see if we can be best friend forever! You can find me at: PetSmart Amherst 1581 Niagara Falls Blvd Amherst, NY 14228 (716) 249-3197 To be able to adopt me you will need to be pre-approved! 10/4/25: two guinea pigs left abandoned at the adoptions entrance between 9:30 and 10:00 am on Saturday 10/4/25. A volunteer witnessed a gentleman walk up to the adoption entrance with his hood up, set the carrier down, and return to a red car parked at the end of the aisle // ALD

10/13/25 - On Saturday, October 4, 2025, surveillance footage captured an individual exiting a red Volkswagen Passat (license plate LBM2755), which was parked at the far end of the lot along the roadway. The individual was wearing a hoodie with the hood pulled up, obscuring their face. They proceeded to walk toward the adoption entrance and placed what appeared to be a box or animal carrier (the exact item is unclear from the footage) in front of the doors. The individual then returned to the vehicle and departed. Investigations conducted a search on the vehicle’s registration, which identified the owner as Miracle Faith McNair (PID 41603313). A cross-reference with our PetPoint system confirmed a matching profile, including name, address, date of birth, and driver’s license number, consistent with the information provided by the police department. Attempts were made to contact Ms. McNair using the two phone numbers listed in her account. One number was unable to receive calls, and the other did not connect to voicemail. The animals involved in this incident are two guinea pigs, identified by PetPoint IDs 59541142 and 59541144. Should Ms. McNair seek to adopt from our organization in the future, she must be approved by a manager prior to proceeding. LJA

column27: Owner came in for recheck of puppy's mouth, spoke with him about spaying this puppy as we RTO'd her as her previous appointment without spaying her. Lana and I explained the possible issues that come with having an intact female (mammary tumors, pyometra) and also since he is likely going rehome her, I explained that she does not need to be reproducing and adding to the dog population. Also that giving birth to multiple litters came be hard on their bodies and they can have complications from giving birth. He asked how much the spay would cost, I told him that since he already paid the $400 in full for her previously treatment that the spay would be part of that cost. He also said that he has unreliable transportation, I told him taht we can keep her over the weekend and have here spayed on Monday then we can arrange for our agents to drop her off to him later in the afternoon on Monday. He agreed to having her spayed on Monday 10/13. I informed the agents about the drop off and Lake said they would make sure to schedule this drop of. PP

column14: Mixed Breed, Medium (up to 44 lbs fully grown)/Mix
column27: Puppy is being spayed on Monday 10/13, agents will be providing transportation for this puppy on Monday afternoon to return to her to owner. PP
